## 4. Escalation Path

| Severity | Response Time | Action |
|----------|--------------|--------|
| **P1 - Critical** | 5 min | Page on-call immediately |
| **P2 - High** | 15 min | Alert on-call via Slack + page |
| **P3 - Medium** | 1 hour | Slack notification, next business day |
| **P4 - Low** | 24 hours | Ticket created, next sprint |

### Contacts
- **On-call primary**: {{ escalation_contact | default(value="see PagerDuty schedule") }}
- **On-call secondary**: {{ escalation_secondary | default(value="see team rotation") }}
- **Engineering lead**: {{ engineering_lead | default(value="see org chart") }}
- **Slack channel**: {{ slack_channel | default(value="#incidents") }}

### Escalation Triggers
- Service down > 5 minutes
- Error rate > 5% for > 10 minutes
- p99 latency > 3x baseline for > 5 minutes
- Data integrity concern (any duration)

---

## 5. Recovery Procedures

### 5.1 Graceful Restart
```bash
# Stop gracefully (allow in-flight requests to complete)
{{ stop_command | default(value="systemctl stop " + service_name | lower | replace(from=" ", to="-")) }}

# Verify process stopped
sleep 3
pgrep -f "{{ process_name | default(value=service_name) }}" && echo "STILL RUNNING" || echo "STOPPED"

# Start
{{ start_command | default(value="systemctl start " + service_name | lower | replace(from=" ", to="-")) }}

# Verify health
sleep 5
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" --connect-timeout 5 http://localhost:{{ port }}{{ health_path | default(value="/health") }}
# Expected: 200
```

### 5.2 Force Restart (if graceful fails)
```bash
# Kill process
pkill -9 -f "{{ process_name | default(value=service_name) }}"

# Clean stale resources (sockets, pid files, lock files)
{{ cleanup_command | default(value="# Add cleanup steps for stale sockets/pid files") }}

# Start fresh
{{ start_command | default(value="systemctl start " + service_name | lower | replace(from=" ", to="-")) }}

# Verify
sleep 5
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" --connect-timeout 5 http://localhost:{{ port }}{{ health_path | default(value="/health") }}
```

### 5.3 Rollback
```bash
# Check current version
{{ version_check_command | default(value="# Add version check command") }}

# Rollback to previous version
{{ rollback_command | default(value="# Add rollback procedure") }}

# Verify rollback
sleep 5
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" --connect-timeout 5 http://localhost:{{ port }}{{ health_path | default(value="/health") }}
```

---

## 6. Post-Incident (Blameless Postmortem)

Complete within **48 hours** of incident resolution.

### Template

```markdown
## Incident Report: [INC-XXXX]

**Date**: YYYY-MM-DD
**Duration**: HH:MM
**Severity**: P1/P2/P3/P4
**Impact**: [What broke, how many users affected]
**Detector**: [Alert, user report, monitoring]

### Timeline
| Time (UTC) | Event |
|-------------|-------|
| HH:MM | Alert triggered |
| HH:MM | On-call acknowledged |
| HH:MM | Root cause identified |
| HH:MM | Mitigation applied |
| HH:MM | Service restored |

### Root Cause
[5 Whys analysis]

### Action Items
| Action | Owner | Due Date | Status |
|--------|-------|----------|--------|
| [Action] | [Name] | YYYY-MM-DD | Open/Done |
```

### Post-Incident Checklist
- [ ] Incident timeline documented
- [ ] Root cause identified (5 Whys)
- [ ] Action items assigned with owners and due dates
- [ ] Monitoring gaps identified and addressed
- [ ] Runbook updated if new failure mode discovered
- [ ] Postmortem shared with team (Slack/wiki)
- [ ] Follow-up scheduled (1 week) to verify action items
